# Jinja2 Template Style Guide

*This rule automatically attaches when working with Jinja template files.*

## Template Structure

- Use template inheritance with `{% extends %}`
- Organize templates with consistent block structure
- Keep template logic minimal (move complex logic to backend)
- Use consistent indentation (2 or 4 spaces)

## Block Organization

Use consistent block structure across templates:

```jinja
{% extends "base.html" %}

{% block head %}
  {# CSS and head content here #}
  <link rel="stylesheet" href="{{ url_for('static', filename='styles.css') }}">
{% endblock %}

{% block content %}
  {# Main content here #}
{% endblock %}

{% block scripts %}
  {# JavaScript at bottom #}
  <script src="{{ url_for('static', filename='app.js') }}"></script>
{% endblock %}
```

## CSS and JavaScript in Jinja

- **CSS**: In `{% block head %}` or `{% block styles %}`
- **JavaScript**: In `{% block scripts %}` at the bottom
- Use `url_for()` for static file paths
- Avoid inline styles and scripts
- Keep external files organized

## Template Variables

- Use descriptive variable names
- Document template variables in comments
- Use default values with `|default()` filter
- Validate/sanitize data in backend, not templates

## Includes and Macros

- Use `{% include %}` for reusable components
- Create macros for repeated patterns
- Organize includes in a consistent directory structure
- Document macro parameters

## Filters and Functions

- Use Jinja filters appropriately (`|safe`, `|escape`, etc.)
- Create custom filters for complex logic
- Keep filter usage consistent
- Understand security implications of filters

## Example Template

```jinja
{% extends "base.html" %}

{% block title %}Page Title{% endblock %}

{% block head %}
  {{ super() }}
  <link rel="stylesheet" href="{{ url_for('static', filename='page.css') }}">
{% endblock %}

{% block content %}
  <div class="container">
    <h1>{{ page_title }}</h1>
    {% include 'components/nav.html' %}
    <!-- Content -->
  </div>
{% endblock %}

{% block scripts %}
  {{ super() }}
  <script src="{{ url_for('static', filename='page.js') }}"></script>
{% endblock %}
```

## Best Practices

- Keep templates DRY (Don't Repeat Yourself)
- Use template inheritance consistently
- Separate presentation from logic
- Use includes for reusable components
- Document template variables and their sources
- Test templates with different data scenarios

## Anti-Patterns

- ❌ Complex logic in templates (move to backend)
- ❌ Inline CSS/JavaScript in templates
- ❌ Mixing template inheritance patterns
- ❌ Unorganized block structure
- ❌ Not using `url_for()` for static files

